6. Create a data viz showing this in the most evident way. Provide your own legend and use themes.

The jitter graph is used to visualize the methods to prepare the main dishes. (Both main_dish and main_prep are discrete variables, hence used jitter graph to visualize). In the below graph we can see the frequency of how main dishes are been prepared. We can clearly see that the most common main dish is turkey and it is baked 422 times.

thanksgivingmeals%>%
  count (main_dish, main_prep, sort=TRUE) %>%
   ggplot(aes(main_prep, n))+
  geom_jitter()+ 
  facet_wrap(~main_dish)+
  coord_flip()+
  geom_text(aes(label = round(n, 1)), size = 2, vjust = -1.25, colour = "blue") +
  theme_test()+
labs(x=" Prepration type ", y= "Frequency", title="Methods to prepare main dishes", caption="Image 1: Jitter")

8. What is the distribution of those who celebrate across income

We can see that the highest number of people i.e 166 celebrate Thanksgiving are in the family income range between $25000 to $49,999. We have used the filter function to first remove the NA values from family income and filtered only those who like to celebrate. Then we have counted the number of people based on family income and those who celebrate thanksgiving and then reorder the information based on family income and the highest number of people who celebrate.

thanksgivingmeals %>% 
  filter (!is.na(family_income), celebrate=="Yes") %>% 
  count (family_income, celebrate, sort = TRUE)%>%
  mutate(family_income = fct_reorder (family_income, n)) %>% 
  kable()

9. Present this information in the most evident way on the data viz.

The best way to represent this information is Bar graph as one variable is continuous and the other is discrete. From this visualization, we can clearly see how many people like to celebrate thanksgiving based on family income. In the ggplot, have used coord_flip to show the bar horizontally just to give a neat presentation, so that the family income range can easily be read. And have used guides(fill =“none”) as the index is not required in this graph.

thanksgivingmeals %>% 
  filter (!is.na(family_income), celebrate=="Yes") %>% 
  count (family_income, celebrate, sort = TRUE) %>%
  group_by(family_income) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(family_income = fct_reorder (family_income, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(family_income, n, fill = family_income)) + 
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()+
  theme_bw() +
  guides( fill ="none")+

  
 labs(x="Family Income range", y= "No. of people who celebrate Thanks giving", title="Celebration of thanks giving based on Income", caption="Image 2 - Bar graph")

13. How do the servings differ by income?

The below table represents how many people order what type of the main dish based on their family income. Here, have used the filter function to filter who celebrates and then filter out certain variables. Then have used the count function and arrange them according to the main dishes so that we can the highest number of people ordering the main dishes based on family income.

thanksgivingmeals%>% 
  filter(celebrate == "Yes")%>%
  filter (main_dish != "None", main_dish != "Other (please specify)", main_dish != "I don't know")%>%
  filter (!is.na(family_income)) %>%
  count (main_dish, family_income) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  kable()
